1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,510
As we enter the new year, we take a look back at some of the biggest space stories of 2024.

2
00:00:10,510 --> 00:00:21,576
Nearly one year ago, a private spacecraft completed the first U.S. moon landing in more than 50 years.

3
00:00:21,576 --> 00:00:36,822
The American space agency NASA announced the space lander, called Odysseus, had touched down on the lunar surface February 22.

4
00:00:36,822 --> 00:00:44,486
Odysseus was developed by the Texas-based company Intuitive Machines.

5
00:00:44,486 --> 00:00:56,807
The spacecraft carried out several science experiments before powering down permanently on the moon in late March.

6
00:00:56,807 --> 00:01:13,781
NASA said Odysseus had successfully captured data to help the agency “better understand the moon’s environment and improve landing precision and safety.”

7
00:01:13,781 --> 00:01:27,841
Japan’s space agency JAXA announced in January 2024 that its SLIM spacecraft had successfully landed on the moon.

8
00:01:27,841 --> 00:01:37,738
But the lander touched down the wrong way up, causing some communication and power problems.

9
00:01:37,738 --> 00:01:47,799
Japanese space officials reported that they stayed in communication with SLIM through late April.

10
00:01:47,799 --> 00:01:58,198
They said the spacecraft was able to collect valuable data about the touchdown and surrounding area.

11
00:01:58,198 --> 00:02:06,077
One purpose of the mission was to demonstrate new precision landing technology.

12
00:02:06,077 --> 00:02:18,200
JAXA said the experiment was successful because SLIM was able to land within 10 meters of its planned target.

13
00:02:18,200 --> 00:02:27,708
In May, China launched its Chang’e 6 spacecraft to the moon’s far side.

14
00:02:27,708 --> 00:02:42,139
In late June, Chinese space officials announced the spacecraft had returned to Earth with rock and soil samples collected on the lunar surface.

15
00:02:42,139 --> 00:02:54,948
The successful return made China the first country to ever collect and bring back lunar samples from the far side of the moon.

16
00:02:54,948 --> 00:03:03,075
The area is known as the far side because it always faces away from Earth.

17
00:03:03,075 --> 00:03:20,967
In October, the European Space Agency (ESA) said it had successfully launched a spacecraft, called Hera, to explore an asteroid struck in an earlier NASA test mission.

18
00:03:20,967 --> 00:03:28,005
Hera’s trip to the asteroid is expected to take about two years.

19
00:03:28,005 --> 00:03:33,057
Hera is headed to the asteroid Dimorphos.

20
00:03:33,057 --> 00:03:45,251
NASA crashed its DART spacecraft into the space rock in 2022, about 11 million kilometers from Earth.

21
00:03:45,251 --> 00:03:58,120
NASA said its mission successfully showed it was possible to change the orbit of asteroids that might threaten Earth in the future.

22
00:03:58,120 --> 00:04:10,115
Hera aims to closely examine Dimorphos to get more details on how the strike by DART affected the asteroid.

23
00:04:10,115 --> 00:04:23,735
The data that NASA collected is to be used together with information gathered by ESA to develop future planetary defense plans.

24
00:04:23,735 --> 00:04:32,608
NASA announced the successful launch of its Europa Clipper spacecraft in October.

25
00:04:32,608 --> 00:04:41,555
The explorer is designed to search for possible signs of life on Jupiter’s moon Europa.

26
00:04:41,555 --> 00:04:49,825
Jupiter is the largest planet in our solar system and has numerous moons.

27
00:04:49,825 --> 00:05:01,656
But icy Europa has been identified by scientists as a good candidate for having the right conditions to support life.

28
00:05:01,656 --> 00:05:11,872
Several studies have suggested the moon likely contains a large ocean beneath its icy surface.

29
00:05:11,872 --> 00:05:26,298
NASA said the Europa Clipper would fly past Mars, then back toward Earth, “using the gravity of each planet to increase its momentum.”

30
00:05:26,298 --> 00:05:38,946
These kinds of “gravity assists” are expected to provide the needed push to get the spacecraft to Jupiter by 2030.

31
00:05:38,946 --> 00:05:59,047
In early June, Boeing successfully carried out a test mission for NASA by transporting two American astronauts – Butch Wilmore and Suni Williams – to the International Space Station (ISS).

32
00:05:59,047 --> 00:06:05,177
The two were expected to stay in space for only a week.

33
00:06:05,177 --> 00:06:13,528
But ongoing technical issues with the Starliner spacecraft prevented a return trip.

34
00:06:13,528 --> 00:06:23,222
NASA announced plans in August to have Starliner return to Earth without the astronauts.

35
00:06:23,222 --> 00:06:36,753
The current plan is for Wilmore and Williams to return on a SpaceX Dragon spacecraft sometime in late March or April.

36
00:06:36,753 --> 00:06:46,037
SpaceX has now completed six launch tests of its huge Starship rocket system.

37
00:06:46,037 --> 00:06:51,408
Four of those tests were carried out in 2024.

38
00:06:51,408 --> 00:06:55,923
The last test took place in November.

39
00:06:55,923 --> 00:07:09,292
The Starship rocket and spacecraft system is designed to be a completely reusable vehicle to transport astronauts and supplies.

40
00:07:09,292 --> 00:07:17,921
It has successfully demonstrated that ability in its most recent experimental flights.

41
00:07:17,921 --> 00:07:32,526
During one of the tests in October, Starship’s Super Heavy booster rocket was "caught“ and secured by a huge structure that includes metal arms.

42
00:07:32,526 --> 00:07:41,914
A short time later, Starship’s second stage safely splashed down in the Indian Ocean.

43
00:07:41,914 --> 00:07:45,136
I’m Bryan Lynn.